In <2ekbm5$d43@rzsun02.rrz.uni-hamburg.de> bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev) writes:

>davide (davide@cad.gatech.edu) writes:

>>   to. I remember someone once mentioned that zips encryption
>>   was trivial to break, and that there was a program that did it.

>The encryption is not very strong, but far from trivial to break. As
>far as I know, nobody can do it on an arbitrary encrypted ZIP archive.

>>   If anyone knows the name of this program, or better yet, what
>>   ftp sight it might be on, can you please send me mail.

>All such programs that I know either use brute force (i.e., try all
>possible passwords), or use a dictionary attack (try a large number of
>dictionary words, because people tend to use them as passwords). The
>first method is essentially useless if a passowrd longer than 6
>characters is used. The second method is useless if the password is
>not in the dictionary used.

>In your particular case, I would advise you to try to recall how your
>password looked like and to create a dictionary containing all those
>forms. A dictionary-based ZIP password cracker is available in source
>from our ftp site:

>ftp.informatik.uni-hamburg.de:/pub/virus/texts/crypto/pkcrack.zip

>It aslo contains a text file, describing the encryption algorithm in
>PKZIP and the archive format.

>Regards,
>Vesselin
